<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="151" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1436,2002]" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,736,1616,1642]" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">
Description of the female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[635,723,1616,1642]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–37" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1875,1899]" captionTargetBox="[197,1396,186,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-22@14.[177,1411,181,1852]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 32–37. female genitalia (coll. ANHRT, unless otherwise indicated). 32, Hampsonola elachistomorpha, Zambia, LGNA 1063; 33, H. aulombardiella, Kenya, LGNA 1299 (coll. A. Kingston); 34, H. argyropasta, holotype of Celama argyropasta, [Ghana] Gold Coast, NHMUK 010317591 (prepared by László) (©NHMUK); 35, Ibidem, Liberia, LGNA 599; 36, H. nanographa, Gabon, LGNA 1228; 37, Cryptonola gen. n. confundata sp. n., paratype, Ivory Coast, LGNA 602." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920087" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920087/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Ovipositor rather short and broad, papilla analis trapezoidal, posterior apophysis moderately long and thick. Eighth tergite very short, medially constricted, anterior apophysis 20% shorter than posterior one, rather thin. Ostium bursae moderately sclerotized, cup-shaped, ductus bursae tubular, relatively long, moderately thick; cervix bursae unmodified, ductus seminalis relatively thick. Distal tubular part of corpus bursae short, ca. one-fifth of bursa length, dilated proximal part of corpus bursae ovoid, with two small, sclerotized, amorphous plates of signa, each bearing very short, acute process; signa situated wide apart from one another.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1436,2002]" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,447,1868,1894]" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">Genetic information.</emphasis>
The species has been assigned the BIN URI: BOLD:AAQ1292. The average intraspecific pairwise distance according to BOLD is 0.40%. The nearest neighbour of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hacker" authorityYear="2012" box="[1041,1218,1904,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanographa">
<emphasis box="[1041,1218,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">H. nanographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="László" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[1262,1436,1905,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Hampsonola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argyropasta">
<emphasis box="[1262,1436,1905,1930]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">H. argyropasta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 3.31% pairwise distance between the two species. The genetic divergence between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hacker" authorityYear="2012" box="[1175,1349,1940,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanographa">
<emphasis box="[1175,1349,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">H. nanographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hacker" baseAuthorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Hampsonola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elachistomorpha">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="151">H. elachistomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is discussed under the latter species.
</paragraph>
